Implementation of Bentley-Ottmann Sweep Line Algorithm to find Intersections of Line Segments¶

Problem Statement¶

Given a set of line segments, compute all the intersection points of these line segments.

Components of the algorithm¶

The algorithm maintains two data structures and a vertical sweepline.

  • The vertical sweepline processes all events from left to right.
  • The Event Queue data structure keeps track of all notable points (events). A point is considered notable if a line segment starts, ends or intersects with other line segments there.
  • The Status Queue data structure maintains the ordering of line segments (by y coordinate), given the current position of the sweepline (its x coordinate).

The algorithm¶

  • The algorithm performs a vertical line sweep processing events from left to right.
  • Initially, all the starting and ending points of the line segments are inserted into the Event Queue.

Key Observation: A line segment must intersect with at least one segment adjacent to it in the Status Queue for it to intersect at all.

  • All adjacent pairs of line segments are checked for intersections which are reported when found.
  • Every time an insertion or a deletion causes a new pair of line segments to be adjacent, they are again checked for intersection. When found, intersections are reported and new events are created and inserted into the Event Queue.
  • The algorithm ends when the Event Queue becomes empty.

Pitfalls:¶

  • This implementation is precise upto 9 decimal places, after which accuracy starts dropping.
  • Two line segments which coincide with each other either partially or in whole have infinitely many points of intersection. This implementation assumes the input does not have any such cases.

The plot of CPU Time against $(n+k) logn$ is approximately linear Therefore, $$ \text{CPU Time} \propto (n+k)logn $$ Hence, this empirically proves the relation $$ T(n, k) = \Theta((n+k)logn) $$
